        <div type="footnotes">
            
            <note xml:id="foot.f1"> The year is established by the reference to CD’s stay in Coniston (see n. 4, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">In <hi rend="italic"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5637.xml">Movement in plants</ref></hi>, p. 304, CD described the cotyledons of a seedling bending perpendicularly downwards at night; the plant later died and was sent to Kew, where it was identified as probably <hi rend="italic">Geranium rotundifolium</hi>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Sanfoin (<hi rend="italic">Onobrychis viciifolia</hi>) is a member of pea family (Fabaceae), and is commonly found in chalk grassland in Britain.</note>  
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD replaced his head gardener, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2906.xml">Henry Lettington</ref>, later in 1879 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12241.xml">letter to J. D. Hooker, 1 October [1879]</ref>, n. 2). The Darwins had stayed in Coniston in the Lake District from 2 to 27 August 1879 (CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II)).</note>    
        </div>
    
